If you&#39;re using **Gradle**, you can add the jar as a normal dependency of your project if you apply the [osgi-run][1] plugin. 

The osgi-run plugin will wrap the jar transparently into a bundle for you, exporting every package in it and calculating all its imports. As Gradle will know the jar&#39;s transitive dependencies, it will do the same for them as well, if necessary.

The jar(s) will be part of the OSGi runtime osgi-run creates, which you can then start up with `gradle runOsgi` or `gradle createOsgi`, then executing either the `run.sh` or `run.bat` scripts.

The actual wrapping is done by [Bnd][2], the swiss knife of the OSGi world, of course.

If you want to configure how the wrapping happens (what should be imported/exported, usually), you can do it easily in the Gradle build file, see the [documentation][3] for details.

Example:

    wrapInstructions {
